00:09:47.590 --> 00:09:49.120
They're not really wave numbers.

00:09:49.120 --> 00:09:52.450
But these three
quantities that have the--

00:09:52.450 --> 00:09:56.500
I mean, these are essentially
spatial periods, aren't they,

00:09:56.500 --> 00:09:58.430
in the three dimensions?

00:09:58.430 --> 00:10:03.070
So these quantities, if you take
the triad of these quantities,

00:10:03.070 --> 00:10:05.050
it is called the wave vector.

00:10:05.050 --> 00:10:07.640
And it is usually--

00:10:07.640 --> 00:10:10.270
we use the same symbol
as the wave number,

00:10:10.270 --> 00:10:12.490
but with the vector now.

00:10:12.490 --> 00:10:19.270
And it consists of the
three components, ky, kz.

00:10:19.270 --> 00:10:22.300
It is a matter of taste
how you write vectors.

00:10:22.300 --> 00:10:23.870
In this class, I actually--

00:10:23.870 --> 00:10:25.180
I will alternate a little bit.

00:10:25.180 --> 00:10:28.060
Sometimes I will write
vectors like this

00:10:28.060 --> 00:10:30.100
as a triad in a parenthesis.

00:10:30.100 --> 00:10:32.110
Sometimes I might
write the vectors

00:10:32.110 --> 00:10:37.870
like this where I
use the unit vector,

00:10:37.870 --> 00:10:39.670
the unit Cartesian vectors.

00:10:39.670 --> 00:10:43.450
Of course-- OK, I hope
that's not confusing.

00:10:43.450 --> 00:10:49.590
One can easily-- clearly
they're both commonly used.

00:10:49.590 --> 00:10:52.590
So that quantity k,
then, is the wave vector.

00:10:57.280 --> 00:11:00.305
And its significance, you
can see it on the slide.

00:11:00.305 --> 00:11:02.680
It's probably better if I
don't attempt to draw it there.

00:11:02.680 --> 00:11:05.380
But you can see it on the slide.

00:11:05.380 --> 00:11:09.580
So the wavefront
of the plane wave

00:11:09.580 --> 00:11:16.380
is a surface which is
perpendicular to the wave

00:11:16.380 --> 00:11:18.730
vector.

00:11:18.730 --> 00:11:21.100
And what is a wavefront?

00:11:21.100 --> 00:11:28.630
Well, wavefront, you
saw it in the movie

00:11:28.630 --> 00:11:30.440
that I played earlier.

00:11:30.440 --> 00:11:36.350
Wavefront is the surface upon
which the phase of the wave

00:11:36.350 --> 00:11:39.100
is constant.

00:11:39.100 --> 00:11:40.460
So what is this?

00:11:40.460 --> 00:11:44.450
This is basically a three
dimensional sinusoid of which

00:11:44.450 --> 00:11:47.490
we only see a 2D slice.

00:11:47.490 --> 00:11:50.350
So this is sinusoid
which alternates.

00:11:50.350 --> 00:11:54.310
The black regions are
negative, minimum.

00:11:54.310 --> 00:11:57.560
I mean they're sort of a
maximum negative value.

00:11:57.560 --> 00:12:02.030
The bright stripes are
maximum positive value.

00:12:02.030 --> 00:12:08.410
And the wavefront is a surface
on which the phase of the wave

00:12:08.410 --> 00:12:09.290
has the same value.

00:12:09.290 --> 00:12:11.740
For example, if
the phase is zero,

00:12:11.740 --> 00:12:14.740
then we're talking
about the positive peak.

00:12:14.740 --> 00:12:16.720
If their phase is pi,
then we're talking

00:12:16.720 --> 00:12:18.700
about the negative
trough, and so

00:12:18.700 --> 00:12:21.740
on, and so forth, or anywhere
in between, for that matter.

00:12:21.740 --> 00:12:24.820
And the wavefront has a
sense of travel to it.

00:12:24.820 --> 00:12:27.100
Because if I play
the movie again,

00:12:27.100 --> 00:12:30.870
then you can see that these
surfaces of constant phase

00:12:30.870 --> 00:12:31.810
are moving.

00:12:31.810 --> 00:12:36.700
This is the sense that the wave
transports energy, if you wish.

00:12:36.700 --> 00:12:41.320
Because the wavefronts are
moving with the wave speed.

00:12:41.320 --> 00:12:44.170
OK, so then we call
it the plane wave,

00:12:44.170 --> 00:12:47.388
because this surface is of
constant phase or planes.

00:12:47.388 --> 00:12:49.180
Of course, you only
see them as lines here.

00:12:49.180 --> 00:12:52.010
Because, again, we're looking
at the slice of the wave.

00:12:52.010 --> 00:12:53.560
But in 3D, they
would be actually

00:12:53.560 --> 00:12:58.880
planes that would be propagating
with the speed of the wave.

00:12:58.880 --> 00:13:01.000
So that is-- so then
the wave vector,

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:02.770
we need it in order
to tell us what

00:13:02.770 --> 00:13:07.270
is the orientation
of these planes.

00:13:07.270 --> 00:13:10.810
And for reasons
of convenience, we

00:13:10.810 --> 00:13:15.400
define it to be perpendicular
to those planes.

00:13:15.400 --> 00:13:20.660
Now, that's one
useful thing to know.

00:13:20.660 --> 00:13:23.340
But that's not all.

00:13:23.340 --> 00:13:29.940
The wave vector, it appears to
be composed of three elements.

00:13:29.940 --> 00:13:33.813
So the question is are these--

00:13:33.813 --> 00:13:35.230
do I really have
three parameters?

00:13:35.230 --> 00:13:38.480
Can I describe a plane
wave with three parameters?

00:13:38.480 --> 00:13:46.890
Well, even before I do any math,
you could probably guess that I

00:13:46.890 --> 00:13:48.300
shouldn't.

00:13:48.300 --> 00:13:50.730
Because these are surfaces.

00:13:50.730 --> 00:13:54.980
These are planar
surfaces in 3D space.

00:13:54.980 --> 00:13:59.580
So I cannot really fit 3
dimensions of planes in a 3D

00:13:59.580 --> 00:14:01.087
space, right?

00:14:01.087 --> 00:14:02.670
Something is wrong
with that argument,

00:14:02.670 --> 00:14:04.590
even without doing any math.

00:14:04.590 --> 00:14:08.740
So in actuality, these three
numbers, kx, ky, and kz,

00:14:08.740 --> 00:14:10.680
they have to be related somehow.

00:14:10.680 --> 00:14:13.780
I cannot arbitrarily
define all three of them.

00:14:13.780 --> 00:14:18.130
But I have to
somehow relate them.

00:14:18.130 --> 00:14:19.800
So the way I relate
them is I actually

00:14:19.800 --> 00:14:23.140
go back to my wave equation.

00:14:23.140 --> 00:14:26.540
And recall this
thing here, the wave,

00:14:26.540 --> 00:14:27.940
which I will call it something.

00:14:27.940 --> 00:14:29.020
What did I call it?

00:14:29.020 --> 00:14:30.560
I didn't call it
anything, actually.

00:14:30.560 --> 00:14:34.790
I just put an amplitude
coefficient in front.

00:14:34.790 --> 00:14:40.210
So the amplitude coefficient,
it is good for completeness,

00:14:40.210 --> 00:14:41.440
I guess.

00:14:41.440 --> 00:14:43.637
And it must satisfy
the wave equation.

00:14:43.637 --> 00:14:44.470
So it must satisfy--

00:14:47.950 --> 00:14:50.000
I'll call it something
now, because--

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:51.830
f, I guess.

00:14:51.830 --> 00:14:57.210
So it is f of x, y, z, t.

00:14:57.210 --> 00:15:00.480
And it must satisfy
this nasty thing, which

00:15:00.480 --> 00:15:09.840
looks like df dx squared plus
df dy squared plus df dz squared

00:15:09.840 --> 00:15:18.210
minus 1 over the velocity now,
d squared f over dt squared.

00:15:18.210 --> 00:15:19.680
It must equal to 0.

00:15:19.680 --> 00:15:21.650
This is what we call
the wave equation.

00:15:21.650 --> 00:15:23.640
And for future
reference, sometimes,

00:15:23.640 --> 00:15:28.900
instead of writing all
these deduced derivatives,

00:15:28.900 --> 00:15:31.290
there's a shorthand
which collapses

00:15:31.290 --> 00:15:33.575
all of this with a symbol del.

00:15:33.575 --> 00:15:34.950
So you can just
write del squared

00:15:34.950 --> 00:15:39.420
f minus 1 over c squared
df dt squared is 0.

00:15:39.420 --> 00:15:42.790
OK, that's the wave equation.

00:15:42.790 --> 00:15:45.560
Very good, so now
what I need to do

00:15:45.560 --> 00:15:50.210
is I need to plug this
expression into the wave

00:15:50.210 --> 00:15:51.038
equation.

00:15:51.038 --> 00:15:51.830
So what expression?

00:15:51.830 --> 00:15:54.050
This expression that
I had for the wave,

00:15:54.050 --> 00:15:56.490
I need to put it
into the equation.

00:15:56.490 --> 00:16:01.430
OK, almost by inspection, we
can see what's going to happen.

00:16:01.430 --> 00:16:04.050
So we have an
exponential, right?

00:16:04.050 --> 00:16:07.670
And if I take one derivative,
the first derivative,

00:16:07.670 --> 00:16:09.680
it will knock out--

00:16:09.680 --> 00:16:14.840
it will multiply by ikx, right,
if I take the x derivative.

00:16:14.840 --> 00:16:17.000
If I take the
second x derivative,

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:20.120
it will bring out another ikx.

00:16:20.120 --> 00:16:23.660
And since i squared
equals minus 1,

00:16:23.660 --> 00:16:28.140
it means that the derivative
will look like this, d--

00:16:28.140 --> 00:16:30.260
let me write it separately here.

00:16:30.260 --> 00:16:31.970
The second derivative,
for example,

00:16:31.970 --> 00:16:34.460
of F with respect
to x squared, it

00:16:34.460 --> 00:16:40.180
will equal minus kx squared
times f itself, right?

00:16:40.180 --> 00:16:43.850
And then it can do the
same for y, and z, and t.

00:16:43.850 --> 00:16:47.870
Except in the case of time, I
will pull out omega squared.

00:16:47.870 --> 00:16:52.400
So if I substitute all of that
now and I put it in, I will get

00:16:52.400 --> 00:17:00.230
that minus kx squared minus
ky squared minus kz squared--

00:17:00.230 --> 00:17:02.470
these are the first
batch of derivatives--

00:17:02.470 --> 00:17:04.790
and then minus omega squared--

00:17:04.790 --> 00:17:09.560
but I have to divide by c also
because c, actually, c squared

00:17:09.560 --> 00:17:10.910
is in the wave equation.

00:17:10.910 --> 00:17:15.140
So all of this, according to the
wave equation, must equal to 0.

00:17:15.140 --> 00:17:18.200
And, of course, it is
possible to satisfy this

00:17:18.200 --> 00:17:19.579
by setting f equal to 0.

00:17:19.579 --> 00:17:21.180
But that's not very interesting.

00:17:21.180 --> 00:17:27.560
So basically what this means,
that this quantity here, it

00:17:27.560 --> 00:17:28.780
must equal to 0.

00:17:28.780 --> 00:17:36.370
So then, as advertised, the
three parameters, kx, ky, kz,

00:17:36.370 --> 00:17:38.630
they're not independent.

00:17:38.630 --> 00:17:42.770
But I can specify two of them.

00:17:42.770 --> 00:17:48.520
The third one is completely
determined by the two

00:17:48.520 --> 00:17:51.950
among the three plus the
frequency of the wave.

00:17:51.950 --> 00:17:55.840
So if I give you
omega, kx, and ky,

00:17:55.840 --> 00:18:00.920
then this equation will force
kz to have a certain value.

00:18:00.920 --> 00:18:03.130
And you can see from
this equation, which

00:18:03.130 --> 00:18:07.896
is written bottom of the
whiteboard and on the slide--

00:18:07.896 --> 00:18:09.722
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:18:09.722 --> 00:18:11.680
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: Oh,
oh, oh, oh, thank you,

00:18:11.680 --> 00:18:12.950
thank you, yes,
because I have a--

00:18:12.950 --> 00:18:13.280
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:18:13.280 --> 00:18:14.780
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
Yes, thank you.

00:18:14.780 --> 00:18:17.180
Because I have a
minus sign here.

00:18:17.180 --> 00:18:20.310
So the extra minus will
become a plus here.

00:18:20.310 --> 00:18:24.220
Yes, OK, now it is correct.

00:18:24.220 --> 00:18:31.467
And so if you look at
this equation now, what

00:18:31.467 --> 00:18:32.175
does it describe?

00:18:34.780 --> 00:18:38.620
If you think of kx, ky, kz,
if you think of them now

00:18:38.620 --> 00:18:41.320
as a new three
dimensional space,

00:18:41.320 --> 00:18:44.890
what is the surface
that the three of them

00:18:44.890 --> 00:18:48.448
are constrained to lie upon?

00:18:48.448 --> 00:18:50.300
Button.

00:18:50.300 --> 00:18:51.550
AUDIENCE: A spherical shell?

00:18:51.550 --> 00:18:53.592
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: It's
a sphere, that's right,

00:18:53.592 --> 00:18:55.870
a shell, the shell
of a sphere, yeah.

00:18:55.870 --> 00:18:58.720
And this sphere is not new
to us who have seen it.

00:18:58.720 --> 00:19:01.660
It actually popped up
in a different context.

00:19:01.660 --> 00:19:04.090
We called it the
Descartes sphere.

00:19:04.090 --> 00:19:10.600
It is actually the
same sphere that--

00:19:10.600 --> 00:19:13.000
actually not even
Descartes, an Arab scientist

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:17.220
in the 11th century,
guessed from Snell's law.

00:19:17.220 --> 00:19:21.640
So it is a little bit, I
guess, magical, or soothing,

00:19:21.640 --> 00:19:24.940
or rewarding, whatever
combination of those

00:19:24.940 --> 00:19:34.420
adjectives you like, that we
found a nice analogy-- or not

00:19:34.420 --> 00:19:36.250
analogy, actually,
we found an agreement

00:19:36.250 --> 00:19:39.400
with geometrical optics.

00:19:39.400 --> 00:19:44.350
In geometrical optics, we said
that the radius of this sphere

00:19:44.350 --> 00:19:46.870
equals 2 pi upon lambda.

00:19:46.870 --> 00:19:49.510
This is now what,
in our new language,

00:19:49.510 --> 00:19:53.530
we call it the wave number,
times the index of refraction,

00:19:53.530 --> 00:19:54.340
n.

00:19:54.340 --> 00:19:57.770
Now this is something that
I haven't told you yet.

00:19:57.770 --> 00:20:01.420
But I will tell you later today.

00:20:01.420 --> 00:20:03.940
In this equation, I
haven't said anything

00:20:03.940 --> 00:20:05.860
about index of refraction.

00:20:05.860 --> 00:20:08.890
However, we know, again
from geometrical optics,

00:20:08.890 --> 00:20:11.620
that c, the speed
of light, depends

00:20:11.620 --> 00:20:13.130
on the index of refraction.

00:20:13.130 --> 00:20:16.150
So another way to derive
this equation is to say--

00:20:16.150 --> 00:20:21.498
to put the free space
speed of light over here.

00:20:21.498 --> 00:20:23.540
And then in order for the
equation to be correct,

00:20:23.540 --> 00:20:26.210
I would have to
multiply by n squared,

00:20:26.210 --> 00:20:27.747
the index of refraction.

00:20:27.747 --> 00:20:29.330
So you can see from
this that, indeed,

00:20:29.330 --> 00:20:30.757
the radius of the sphere.

00:20:30.757 --> 00:20:33.090
Oh, and of course, to compute
the radius of this sphere,

00:20:33.090 --> 00:20:38.630
I have to use, once again,
these dispersion relations.

00:20:38.630 --> 00:20:40.410
So the radius of
this sphere, if you

00:20:40.410 --> 00:20:45.420
look from this equation over
here, the radius of this sphere

00:20:45.420 --> 00:20:52.470
is k, the magnitude
of the wave vector.

00:20:52.470 --> 00:21:00.420
It must equal n omega
over c free space.

00:21:00.420 --> 00:21:02.680
OK, and now it is a
matter of preference

00:21:02.680 --> 00:21:04.060
how you want to do it.

00:21:04.060 --> 00:21:08.950
For example, you can
write omega as 2 pi times

00:21:08.950 --> 00:21:12.050
nu, where nu is
of the frequency.

00:21:12.050 --> 00:21:15.810
Remember, omega is the
angular frequency--

00:21:15.810 --> 00:21:17.590
over cfs.

00:21:17.590 --> 00:21:19.540
Then you can use the
dispersion relation,

00:21:19.540 --> 00:21:25.030
which says that c free
space equals lambda nu.

00:21:25.030 --> 00:21:26.600
So nu will cancel.

00:21:26.600 --> 00:21:32.850
And you end up with n times
2 pi over lambda free space.

00:21:35.750 --> 00:21:38.737
And, of course, nu--

00:21:38.737 --> 00:21:40.320
I don't say anything
about free space,

00:21:40.320 --> 00:21:42.120
because nu is the
same everywhere,

00:21:42.120 --> 00:21:44.400
whether it is free
space, or a slave--

00:21:44.400 --> 00:21:46.020
I mean, not free space.

00:21:46.020 --> 00:21:47.320
I'm sorry.

00:21:47.320 --> 00:21:49.530
OK, so that's where this
equation comes from.

00:21:49.530 --> 00:21:52.105
That's why the radius
of the k sphere,

00:21:52.105 --> 00:21:56.340
it equals n omega
over the free--

00:21:56.340 --> 00:22:00.840
over the speed of light
in a vacuum or 2 pi

00:22:00.840 --> 00:22:03.350
n over lambda, the
wavelength in free space.

00:22:07.040 --> 00:22:08.120
Now, those of you--

00:22:08.120 --> 00:22:10.730
some of you may have
taken solid state.

00:22:10.730 --> 00:22:14.090
This k sphere also
comes up there.

00:22:14.090 --> 00:22:17.940
And it is called
the Ewald sphere.

00:22:17.940 --> 00:22:21.560
In our language in optics, we
seldom call it Ewald sphere.

00:22:21.560 --> 00:22:25.730
We call it k sphere
or Descartes sphere.

00:22:25.730 --> 00:22:30.500
But all of these three terms,
all of these three names,

00:22:30.500 --> 00:22:34.340
they actually denote
the same thing.

00:22:34.340 --> 00:22:36.920
And, of course, in the
case of solid state,

00:22:36.920 --> 00:22:44.270
this sphere does not
apply to light usually.

00:22:44.270 --> 00:22:45.260
But it applies to what?

00:22:49.472 --> 00:22:52.117
Button?

00:22:52.117 --> 00:22:52.950
AUDIENCE: Electrons.

00:22:52.950 --> 00:22:55.033
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: To
electrons, that's correct.

00:22:55.033 --> 00:22:58.200
So according to
quantum mechanics,

00:22:58.200 --> 00:23:00.650
electrons are also waves.

00:23:00.650 --> 00:23:04.230
And they satisfy-- actually that
don't satisfy this equation.

00:23:04.230 --> 00:23:06.400
They satisfy the
Schroedinger equation,

00:23:06.400 --> 00:23:09.690
which is in one of the
problems of the homework.

00:23:09.690 --> 00:23:11.640
So anyway, so
Schroedinger equation

00:23:11.640 --> 00:23:14.810
similarly leads to a
sphere like this one.

00:23:20.830 --> 00:23:22.300
Is there one thing that--

00:23:22.300 --> 00:23:26.790
OK, so this is a sort of
preliminary introduction

00:23:26.790 --> 00:23:28.350
to plane waves.

00:23:28.350 --> 00:23:34.620
One thing that I would like
to very strongly emphasize

00:23:34.620 --> 00:23:37.740
is this expression over here,
the complex exponential--

00:23:37.740 --> 00:23:39.690
I will rewrite it once again.

00:23:44.450 --> 00:23:55.410
e to the i kx x plus ky y
plus kz z minus omega t,

00:23:55.410 --> 00:23:58.510
OK, this expression,
when we see that,

00:23:58.510 --> 00:24:02.860
when we see an exponential
with linear terms

00:24:02.860 --> 00:24:06.070
in the Cartesian coordinates,
that's a plane wave.

00:24:06.070 --> 00:24:07.300
And now you know why, right?

00:24:07.300 --> 00:24:10.730
Because it corresponds
to this moving wavefront.

00:24:10.730 --> 00:24:12.890
And, of course,
most of the time,

00:24:12.890 --> 00:24:14.620
we will not add it like this.

00:24:14.620 --> 00:24:18.640
We will omit this term
because of the phasor business

00:24:18.640 --> 00:24:21.070
that we discussed last time.

00:24:21.070 --> 00:24:23.140
So we will actually
see it like this.

00:24:23.140 --> 00:24:27.370
And also, very often, when--

00:24:27.370 --> 00:24:29.500
several things that
happen in here.

00:24:29.500 --> 00:24:34.310
For one thing, these three
numbers, as I said before,

00:24:34.310 --> 00:24:35.640
they're not free.

00:24:35.640 --> 00:24:40.250
So they are given by kx
squared plus ky squared plus kz

00:24:40.250 --> 00:24:45.560
squared equals omega
over c squared or--

00:25:04.150 --> 00:25:04.660
OK.

00:25:04.660 --> 00:25:10.330
This is another way
of solving the sphere.

00:25:10.330 --> 00:25:14.490
So we will see these
kinds of expressions.

00:25:14.490 --> 00:25:17.120
For example, I might
write something like e

00:25:17.120 --> 00:25:24.110
to the i kx x plus ky y plus.

00:25:34.440 --> 00:25:39.175
And there's a z here
outside of the square root.

00:25:39.175 --> 00:25:40.550
So this looks a
little bit scary.

00:25:40.550 --> 00:25:42.230
But it doesn't need to be scary.

00:25:42.230 --> 00:25:44.210
It a plane wave.

00:25:44.210 --> 00:25:47.550
And we will see expressions like
this one later in the class.

00:25:47.550 --> 00:25:49.610
But I want to sort
of prepare you now

00:25:49.610 --> 00:25:53.330
so that they are associated
with a physical meaning

00:25:53.330 --> 00:25:54.540
in your minds.

00:25:54.540 --> 00:25:56.330
It is not just an expression.

00:25:56.330 --> 00:25:58.360
It's actually
denotes a plane wave.

00:25:58.360 --> 00:26:01.100
The two linear terms here--
actually, all three are

00:26:01.100 --> 00:26:05.420
linear. x, y, and z
appear as first powers.

00:26:05.420 --> 00:26:08.870
And the reason this
square root appears here

00:26:08.870 --> 00:26:12.460
is because of the Descartes
sphere, or the Ewald sphere,

00:26:12.460 --> 00:26:14.050
or whichever.

00:26:14.050 --> 00:26:20.838
OK, any questions
about plane waves?

00:26:35.490 --> 00:26:39.280
The other wave that we'll
be dealing with quite a bit

00:26:39.280 --> 00:26:41.890
is the spherical wave.

00:26:41.890 --> 00:26:51.420
And so clearly, as the name
suggests, in this case,

00:26:51.420 --> 00:26:55.800
you have spherical wavefronts,
which are either going away

00:26:55.800 --> 00:27:01.830
from a source, a diverging wave,
or inwards, a converging wave.

00:27:01.830 --> 00:27:06.670
Just as an aside,
by the way, I should

00:27:06.670 --> 00:27:12.910
emphasize that the spherical
wave is not a physical thing.

00:27:12.910 --> 00:27:17.060
So plane wave is not
physical either, by the way.

00:27:17.060 --> 00:27:18.880
Why is the plane
wave not physical?

00:27:18.880 --> 00:27:21.880
I mean, what's an obvious
reason why a plane wave must be

00:27:21.880 --> 00:27:23.210
an approximation of something?

00:27:23.210 --> 00:27:23.710
Button.

00:27:28.402 --> 00:27:30.360
AUDIENCE: Energy of the
plane wave is infinite.

00:27:30.360 --> 00:27:30.660
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
That's right.

00:27:30.660 --> 00:27:32.010
It has infinite energy.

00:27:32.010 --> 00:27:34.060
It is infinitely large.

00:27:34.060 --> 00:27:37.400
So, clearly, I cannot
create plane waves per se.

00:27:37.400 --> 00:27:42.510
I can only create sort of finite
approximations to plane waves.

00:27:42.510 --> 00:27:45.240
A spherical wave is--

00:27:45.240 --> 00:27:48.300
but nevertheless, it is
an interesting thing.

00:27:48.300 --> 00:27:50.760
And the reason we spend
all this time defining it

00:27:50.760 --> 00:27:54.720
is because it provides a lot
of mathematical convenience

00:27:54.720 --> 00:27:57.660
in dealing with more
realistic waves, waves

00:27:57.660 --> 00:27:59.070
that can be realized.

00:27:59.070 --> 00:28:02.130
I can express them in terms
of this fictitious entity,

00:28:02.130 --> 00:28:05.147
the plane wave.

00:28:05.147 --> 00:28:06.730
The same is true for
the point source,

00:28:06.730 --> 00:28:10.150
but for a slightly
different reason.

00:28:10.150 --> 00:28:13.690
It is actually impossible to
create an ideal spherical wave.

00:28:13.690 --> 00:28:16.870
The best thing you can do is
you can create a wave that

00:28:16.870 --> 00:28:20.330
would sort of, if you--

00:28:22.990 --> 00:28:26.710
well, the only-- the best
thing that you can do

00:28:26.710 --> 00:28:29.240
is you can create a
dipole source here.

00:28:29.240 --> 00:28:31.330
So if you aim the
dipole the same,

00:28:31.330 --> 00:28:33.760
the vertical direction,
then what you can do

00:28:33.760 --> 00:28:37.000
is you can create a
radiation pattern that

00:28:37.000 --> 00:28:41.590
has approximately 60, or
actually, 120 degrees opening,

00:28:41.590 --> 00:28:43.570
126, to be--

00:28:43.570 --> 00:28:45.090
63, isn't it?

00:28:45.090 --> 00:28:48.850
I think it's 63
degrees, the dipole.

00:28:48.850 --> 00:28:51.520
Anyway, so you can create a
direction pattern like this,

00:28:51.520 --> 00:28:53.680
but never quite
a spherical wave.

00:28:53.680 --> 00:28:56.080
In fact, someone as
famous as Einstein

00:28:56.080 --> 00:29:00.220
said that spherical
waves don't exist.

00:29:00.220 --> 00:29:02.170
Nevertheless, it is
a very convenient

00:29:02.170 --> 00:29:03.430
mathematical quantity.

00:29:03.430 --> 00:29:06.800
And that's why
we're describing it.

00:29:06.800 --> 00:29:11.110
But again, by the way, this
is true in any kind of physics

00:29:11.110 --> 00:29:12.970
that you might learn.

00:29:12.970 --> 00:29:14.918
For example, in
mechanics, very often

00:29:14.918 --> 00:29:16.085
you deal with frictionless--

00:29:16.085 --> 00:29:16.480
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:29:16.480 --> 00:29:17.160
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
Is [INAUDIBLE]??

00:29:17.160 --> 00:29:17.770
Yeah.

00:29:17.770 --> 00:29:23.330
AUDIENCE: Suppose you burst a
small cracker in a water tank?

00:29:23.330 --> 00:29:25.720
Then it wouldn't--
wouldn't it be?

00:29:25.720 --> 00:29:26.910
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: Oh, I'm
sorry, I meant only in optics.

00:29:26.910 --> 00:29:27.200
AUDIENCE: Optics.

00:29:27.200 --> 00:29:28.510
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
Yeah, in water tank,

00:29:28.510 --> 00:29:30.360
possibly you can create
a spherical wave.

00:29:30.360 --> 00:29:31.818
Even so, it's not
a spherical wave.

00:29:31.818 --> 00:29:33.010
Because it is finite, right?

00:29:33.010 --> 00:29:34.240
It has a finite source.

00:29:36.990 --> 00:29:39.240
Anyway, the reason in optics
you can fundamentally not

00:29:39.240 --> 00:29:41.950
create this kind of thing is
because of charge conservation.

00:29:41.950 --> 00:29:45.370
You cannot-- in order to create
a spherical wave like this,

00:29:45.370 --> 00:29:48.300
you would have to create
an oscillating charge here.

00:29:48.300 --> 00:29:50.470
And no such thing exists.

00:29:50.470 --> 00:29:53.160
So the only thing you can do
is you can create a dipole.

00:29:53.160 --> 00:29:56.070
That is two charges which are
alternating, up and down, up

00:29:56.070 --> 00:29:57.900
and down, positive and negative.

00:29:57.900 --> 00:30:02.510
That would result in a wave
that it looks approximately

00:30:02.510 --> 00:30:05.820
like a spherical wave, but only
in the direction perpendicular

00:30:05.820 --> 00:30:07.130
to the dipole.

00:30:07.130 --> 00:30:09.090
In the direction along
the dipole axis, it

00:30:09.090 --> 00:30:10.490
actually, the wave vanishes.

00:30:10.490 --> 00:30:13.820
So it is very different
than a spherical wave.

00:30:18.490 --> 00:30:22.360
To justify it a little bit why,
even though it is non-physical,

00:30:22.360 --> 00:30:25.550
why we spend so much
time discussing it,

00:30:25.550 --> 00:30:30.060
it has to do, actually,
with systems theory.

00:30:30.060 --> 00:30:31.780
Yes, question?

00:30:31.780 --> 00:30:34.180
AUDIENCE: Isn't a dipole
actually canceling out

00:30:34.180 --> 00:30:40.110
because of the distance between
the top and bottom source?

00:30:40.110 --> 00:30:42.300
You have like a different
distance between them.

00:30:42.300 --> 00:30:44.430
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: The
charge, the charge is 0.

00:30:44.430 --> 00:30:45.097
The charge is 0.

00:30:45.097 --> 00:30:46.555
But you still have
a dipole moment.

00:30:46.555 --> 00:30:48.840
Then moreover, if the dipole
is oscillating, that is,

00:30:48.840 --> 00:30:50.700
if it is going from
positive to negative,

00:30:50.700 --> 00:30:53.700
positive to negative
very, very fast, then you

00:30:53.700 --> 00:30:54.870
have charges accelerating.

00:30:54.870 --> 00:30:57.440
So therefore you generate
electromagnetic radiation,

00:30:57.440 --> 00:30:58.790
as we will see in a little bit.

00:30:58.790 --> 00:31:01.920
AUDIENCE: No, no, I
mean the intensity

00:31:01.920 --> 00:31:05.580
of the field from the
dipole isn't necessarily

00:31:05.580 --> 00:31:09.240
vanishing along the axis if the
spacing's set the right way.

00:31:12.945 --> 00:31:15.070
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: Not
everywhere along the axis,

00:31:15.070 --> 00:31:17.112
but you will definitely
get nulls along the axis.

00:31:22.870 --> 00:31:24.755
If I remember correctly,
yeah, the dipole

00:31:24.755 --> 00:31:26.630
has a radiation pattern
that looks like this.

00:31:26.630 --> 00:31:28.370
It looks like a butterfly.

00:31:28.370 --> 00:31:31.200
AUDIENCE: Yeah, but it's
dependent on the distance

00:31:31.200 --> 00:31:34.500
between the plus and
the minus charges.

00:31:34.500 --> 00:31:36.000
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
No, I'm talking

00:31:36.000 --> 00:31:38.340
about an infinitesimally
small dipole now.

00:31:38.340 --> 00:31:39.132
AUDIENCE: OK, cool.

00:31:39.132 --> 00:31:40.507
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
Yeah, if you

00:31:40.507 --> 00:31:42.255
have like a lambda
over four and 10

00:31:42.255 --> 00:31:43.660
or something like
that, then yes,

00:31:43.660 --> 00:31:46.170
the radiation pattern
looks different.

00:31:46.170 --> 00:31:49.500
But in the simplest possible
case that you can approximate

00:31:49.500 --> 00:31:53.730
the best spherical wave is an
infinitesimally small dipole

00:31:53.730 --> 00:31:56.950
whose radiation pattern
looks like a butterfly.

00:32:02.727 --> 00:32:05.060
So we actually went a little
bit ahead of ourselves now.

00:32:05.060 --> 00:32:06.840
Because this entire
discussion, it

00:32:06.840 --> 00:32:09.350
involved electromagnetics,
which we haven't done yet.

00:32:09.350 --> 00:32:12.360
But by the end of
this lecture, it

00:32:12.360 --> 00:32:13.860
will be a little
bit more clear what

00:32:13.860 --> 00:32:16.970
I mean by dipoles and
all of these things.

00:32:16.970 --> 00:32:20.870
The thing I meant to say
is that the spherical wave,

00:32:20.870 --> 00:32:25.300
mathematically, it
corresponds to a point source.

00:32:25.300 --> 00:32:30.230
And that is something that
most of you, probably,

00:32:30.230 --> 00:32:34.430
at some point or another,
took a class on linear systems

00:32:34.430 --> 00:32:40.725
where typically you learn a
term called an impulse response.

00:32:40.725 --> 00:32:42.350
So the impulse pulse
in the time domain

00:32:42.350 --> 00:32:45.850
is a very narrow excitation.

00:32:45.850 --> 00:32:48.700
In fact, it is
infinitesimally narrow.

00:32:48.700 --> 00:32:50.360
And it is so narrow
that, because it

00:32:50.360 --> 00:32:53.570
has to carry finite energy, it
also has infinite amplitude.

00:32:53.570 --> 00:32:55.680
That's what it's
called an impulse.

00:32:55.680 --> 00:32:58.290
So the spherical wave is
the equivalent of that,

00:32:58.290 --> 00:32:59.840
but in space now.

00:32:59.840 --> 00:33:03.920
The spherical wave originates
as an infinitesimally small

00:33:03.920 --> 00:33:09.200
disturbance, if you wish, which
then mathematically creates

00:33:09.200 --> 00:33:15.552
this uniformly or isotropically
expanding spherical wavefront.

00:33:15.552 --> 00:33:17.510
And from that point of
view, it is very useful.

00:33:17.510 --> 00:33:20.210
Because even the dipole
that I said before,

00:33:20.210 --> 00:33:22.700
it can be described,
actually, as a superposition

00:33:22.700 --> 00:33:24.730
of a spherical wave.

00:33:24.730 --> 00:33:34.320
So I can be physically correct
if I do my physics correct.

00:33:34.320 --> 00:33:37.000
I can get the proper answer.

00:33:37.000 --> 00:33:39.990
So the spherical wave provides
this mathematical convenience.

00:33:39.990 --> 00:33:42.530
Also, to be honest, the
math that we will do here,

00:33:42.530 --> 00:33:44.310
it is a very good
approximation to what

00:33:44.310 --> 00:33:45.750
you observe in the laboratory.

00:33:45.750 --> 00:33:48.750
That's another good
justification for using it.

00:33:48.750 --> 00:33:50.760
Because even though
we know that there

00:33:50.760 --> 00:33:53.790
is no such thing
as a point source,

00:33:53.790 --> 00:33:56.670
many of the things that we
will derive in the next two

00:33:56.670 --> 00:34:01.030
lectures based in this sort
of crude approximation,

00:34:01.030 --> 00:34:03.900
they tend now to be very
good approximations for what

00:34:03.900 --> 00:34:05.400
you see in the laboratory.

00:34:05.400 --> 00:34:08.280
For example, if
you take a pinhole,

00:34:08.280 --> 00:34:09.900
a pinhole is a
finite thing, right?

00:34:09.900 --> 00:34:12.480
I mean, the smallest
pinhole that people

00:34:12.480 --> 00:34:16.139
use in the laboratory, it may
have a diameter of one micron.

00:34:16.139 --> 00:34:18.449
Sometimes we use bigger,
three, five micron,

00:34:18.449 --> 00:34:19.429
something like that.

00:34:19.429 --> 00:34:21.179
Well, if you pass light
through a pinhole,

00:34:21.179 --> 00:34:23.610
the light that comes out is,
to a very good approximation,

00:34:23.610 --> 00:34:27.070
described by a spherical wave,
but of course not everywhere,

00:34:27.070 --> 00:34:27.570
right?

00:34:27.570 --> 00:34:30.250
The light coming
out of a pinhole,

00:34:30.250 --> 00:34:31.570
it doesn't come out backwards.

00:34:31.570 --> 00:34:33.250
It only goes forward, right?

00:34:33.250 --> 00:34:37.409
So therefore, you have-- you
know, clearly, the expression

00:34:37.409 --> 00:34:39.600
is approximately
correct, but only

00:34:39.600 --> 00:34:44.300
for the part of the wave,
the portion that is physical.

00:34:44.300 --> 00:34:47.070
So we have to be a little
bit mindful of what

00:34:47.070 --> 00:34:50.310
is the meaning of everything
that we write down,

00:34:50.310 --> 00:34:55.014
especially when things
like that are involved.

00:34:55.014 --> 00:34:56.639
The spherical wave
has another problem.

00:34:56.639 --> 00:35:01.150
It has the problem that
it blows up at the center.

00:35:01.150 --> 00:35:04.140
And the reason it
blows up is because--

00:35:04.140 --> 00:35:07.350
well, like the impulse
in the time domain

00:35:07.350 --> 00:35:12.980
that you learned in
linear dynamical systems,

00:35:12.980 --> 00:35:15.720
it has to have a finite energy.

00:35:15.720 --> 00:35:18.000
So in this context
here, the finite energy,

00:35:18.000 --> 00:35:21.930
as you proved in the
homework some time ago,

00:35:21.930 --> 00:35:25.260
it means that the amplitude
of this spherical wave

00:35:25.260 --> 00:35:29.100
must decrease like
one over the distance.

00:35:29.100 --> 00:35:32.050
So this 1 over r that we get
in the denominator, of course,

00:35:32.050 --> 00:35:33.950
at r equals 0, it
explodes, right?

00:35:33.950 --> 00:35:39.020
So, again, that is the delta
function, the impulse analogy.

00:35:39.020 --> 00:35:42.650
So the spherical wave has a
few mathematical inconveniences

00:35:42.650 --> 00:35:44.810
of this sort that we
have to be mindful with.

00:35:49.570 --> 00:35:53.900
Now, there's one more
mysterious thing about it,

00:35:53.900 --> 00:35:55.270
which I will just point out.

00:35:55.270 --> 00:35:59.372
And I will then move
on without saying why.

00:35:59.372 --> 00:36:01.580
If you look at the expression
of the spherical wave--

00:36:01.580 --> 00:36:02.455
let me write it down.

00:36:02.455 --> 00:36:16.770
It looks like cosine kr
minus omega t over r.

00:36:16.770 --> 00:36:21.040
And let's take stock here.

00:36:21.040 --> 00:36:22.570
So the 1 over r we discussed.

00:36:22.570 --> 00:36:24.330
The 1 over r is
energy conservation.

00:36:24.330 --> 00:36:26.280
We always like that.

00:36:26.280 --> 00:36:30.030
The cosine that you
see in the numerator,

00:36:30.030 --> 00:36:39.514
if I go back and play the
movie of the spherical wave,

00:36:39.514 --> 00:36:42.910
we have to wait for the
plane wave to finish here.

00:36:42.910 --> 00:36:45.900
So the kr minus omega
t, it is this sort

00:36:45.900 --> 00:36:50.770
of explosion of the wavefronts
that you see in the movie.

00:36:50.770 --> 00:36:57.110
So kr, if i is the radius, kr
describes this sphere again.

00:36:57.110 --> 00:37:00.520
So the cosine kr
basically tells you

00:37:00.520 --> 00:37:03.880
that you have these alternating
positive and negative

00:37:03.880 --> 00:37:06.100
valued spheres.

00:37:06.100 --> 00:37:08.500
And the minus omega t
is the traveling aspect.

00:37:08.500 --> 00:37:11.140
It tells you that
these spheres explode.

00:37:11.140 --> 00:37:14.960
They propagate outwards
as a function of time.

00:37:14.960 --> 00:37:18.800
So this is the meaning
of the kr minus omega t.

00:37:18.800 --> 00:37:20.980
Then it bothers to put
another term over there,

00:37:20.980 --> 00:37:23.350
minus pi over 2.

00:37:23.350 --> 00:37:25.450
And this might sound
a little bit weird.

00:37:25.450 --> 00:37:30.460
I mean, in general, you can put
any phase that you like there.

00:37:30.460 --> 00:37:36.760
It means that you have
a shifted time axis.

00:37:36.760 --> 00:37:38.200
So I could put 5 there.

00:37:38.200 --> 00:37:39.790
Why did they bother
to put pi over 2?

00:37:39.790 --> 00:37:42.460
What is the pi
over 2 relative to?

00:37:42.460 --> 00:37:47.240
OK, it turns out if you properly
solve Maxwell's equations,

00:37:47.240 --> 00:37:49.000
which we haven't
seen yet, but I'm

00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:51.760
sure you are aware that
there is such a thing called

00:37:51.760 --> 00:37:54.610
Maxwell's equation
that describes

00:37:54.610 --> 00:37:55.680
electromagnetic waves.

00:37:55.680 --> 00:38:01.210
OK, so if you solve it properly
with this kind of point source,

00:38:01.210 --> 00:38:05.360
because of something having
to do with magnetic fields,

00:38:05.360 --> 00:38:07.990
you pick up a phase delay
with respect to what?

00:38:07.990 --> 00:38:10.730
You pick up a phase delay
with respect to the source.

00:38:10.730 --> 00:38:12.070
So this is now really weird.

00:38:12.070 --> 00:38:14.980
It tells you if you have a
source that is oscillating,

00:38:14.980 --> 00:38:19.450
let's say, like a cosine, so
it is maximum at t equals 0,

00:38:19.450 --> 00:38:22.240
the wave that comes out
will actually be a sine.

00:38:22.240 --> 00:38:24.910
So it will be phase
shifted by pi over 2.

00:38:24.910 --> 00:38:29.670
There's no easy way to explain
this either than solving

00:38:29.670 --> 00:38:30.910
Maxwell's equation.

00:38:30.910 --> 00:38:35.120
There is actually some papers in
the literature-- this is very,

00:38:35.120 --> 00:38:37.230
very interesting for an--

00:38:37.230 --> 00:38:38.520
I don't know.

00:38:38.520 --> 00:38:40.277
it's strange, right?

00:38:40.277 --> 00:38:41.860
It can be explained
from the equation,

00:38:41.860 --> 00:38:43.460
but it's still a
little bit strange.

00:38:43.460 --> 00:38:46.380
So people are actually
working on this phase shift.

00:38:46.380 --> 00:38:49.390
There's some very
strange aspects to it.

00:38:49.390 --> 00:38:52.450
Anyway, for us, the phase
shift, we'll just accept it.

00:38:52.450 --> 00:38:53.860
It is well established.

00:38:53.860 --> 00:38:57.850
So we'll just accept
it and move on.

00:38:57.850 --> 00:39:00.690
When we write it
as a phasor, I mean

00:39:00.690 --> 00:39:03.700
in the complex
presentation, of course,

00:39:03.700 --> 00:39:08.180
e to the minus i pi
over 2 is minus i.

00:39:08.180 --> 00:39:10.760
So I skipped a few
steps of the slide.

00:39:10.760 --> 00:39:12.690
So let me do them
on the whiteboard.

00:39:12.690 --> 00:39:15.320
So to go from this in
the complex presentation,

00:39:15.320 --> 00:39:21.350
you would write e to the i, kr
minus omega t minus pi over 2.

00:39:21.350 --> 00:39:23.930
And, of course, you still
have this thing outside.

00:39:23.930 --> 00:39:28.300
Nothing can-- this
is not affected.

00:39:28.300 --> 00:39:30.890
OK, then remember
that e to the minus

00:39:30.890 --> 00:39:34.820
i pi over 2 equals minus i.

00:39:34.820 --> 00:39:36.590
And it equals 1 over i.

00:39:36.590 --> 00:39:41.380
So this is why the i appeared
in the denominator over here.

00:39:41.380 --> 00:39:44.010
So because pi over
2 is kind of a pain

00:39:44.010 --> 00:39:46.520
to write down, when we
write the spherical way,

00:39:46.520 --> 00:39:50.130
we'll just write it with
the i in the denominator.

00:39:50.130 --> 00:39:51.600
And this i is actually not--

00:39:51.600 --> 00:39:54.700
I mean, it's not a
big deal, you know.

00:39:54.700 --> 00:40:00.910
If you-- in fact, myself,
sometimes I will just skip it.

00:40:00.910 --> 00:40:03.640
But it's kind of nice
to know that it's there.

00:40:06.240 --> 00:40:08.830
And, of course, in
the-- the other thing

00:40:08.830 --> 00:40:10.590
that we'll do
commonly, but by now

00:40:10.590 --> 00:40:13.260
a thing where we're
comfortable with that

00:40:13.260 --> 00:40:19.110
is that we neglect the
temporal variation.

00:40:19.110 --> 00:40:20.360
And then we'll get the phasor.

00:40:24.000 --> 00:40:26.880
The last thing that we'll do
before moving on to a slightly

00:40:26.880 --> 00:40:30.150
different topic is--

00:40:30.150 --> 00:40:32.010
remember in
geometrical optics, we

00:40:32.010 --> 00:40:34.650
derived a lot of
useful things using

00:40:34.650 --> 00:40:36.750
this paraxial approximation.

00:40:36.750 --> 00:40:39.700
So the paraxial approximation
basically says that--

00:40:43.020 --> 00:40:48.330
in this case, the wave
originated relatively far away.

00:40:48.330 --> 00:40:50.370
And you have these
spherical wavefronts

00:40:50.370 --> 00:40:53.850
which are nice spheres
near the source.

00:40:53.850 --> 00:40:59.270
But if you go at a relatively
long distance, basically,

00:40:59.270 --> 00:41:01.730
you cannot tell the difference
between these spherical

00:41:01.730 --> 00:41:04.490
wavefronts and parabolas.

00:41:04.490 --> 00:41:06.830
And it turns out that,
because the sphere involves

00:41:06.830 --> 00:41:09.860
this nasty square
root, it is much more

00:41:09.860 --> 00:41:12.820
convenient to represent
this as parabolas.

00:41:12.820 --> 00:41:15.430
So the way you go from the
sphere to the parabola,

00:41:15.430 --> 00:41:16.402
I did it on the slide.

00:41:16.402 --> 00:41:17.360
And I will do it again.

00:41:17.360 --> 00:41:19.610
Because this is a
derivation I want

00:41:19.610 --> 00:41:21.860
you to be very familiar with.

00:41:21.860 --> 00:41:23.060
We've done it a few times.

00:41:23.060 --> 00:41:25.220
And we'll do it again and again.

00:41:25.220 --> 00:41:28.920
You start with the
expression for the wave.

00:41:28.920 --> 00:41:32.000
So it is e to the ikr, right?

00:41:32.000 --> 00:41:33.620
And there is bells and whistles.

00:41:33.620 --> 00:41:34.533
There is all the r's.

00:41:34.533 --> 00:41:35.200
There's the i's.

00:41:35.200 --> 00:41:36.990
Let me just write this.

00:41:36.990 --> 00:41:40.550
OK, and then remember,
so we have r.

00:41:40.550 --> 00:41:42.620
This is the polar coordinate.

00:41:42.620 --> 00:41:47.280
So it is x plus
y plus z squared.

00:41:47.280 --> 00:41:49.370
And the paraxial approximation--

00:41:49.370 --> 00:41:51.800
let me put this back--

00:41:51.800 --> 00:41:57.300
in our convention, usually,
is that this is the z-axis.

00:41:59.870 --> 00:42:04.110
So z is the axis of
propagation, the optical axis.

00:42:04.110 --> 00:42:07.060
And then you have the other
two axes perpendicular to it.

00:42:07.060 --> 00:42:10.260
Typically, we'll denote
x as being vertical.

00:42:10.260 --> 00:42:13.880
OK, and is this now right
handed, the way I did it?

00:42:13.880 --> 00:42:16.080
Yeah, right hand, OK good.

00:42:16.080 --> 00:42:18.650
All right, so the
paraxial approximation

00:42:18.650 --> 00:42:22.910
then means that z is much
bigger than the values

00:42:22.910 --> 00:42:24.320
of the other two coordinates.

00:42:24.320 --> 00:42:26.660
Because, basically,
I'm limiting myself

00:42:26.660 --> 00:42:29.120
to operate in this region.

00:42:29.120 --> 00:42:31.800
that's the meaning of the
paraxial approximation.

00:42:31.800 --> 00:42:34.100
So what you do then is
you do a Taylor expansion

00:42:34.100 --> 00:42:35.840
on this square root.

00:42:35.840 --> 00:42:37.880
So you pull z outside.

00:42:46.290 --> 00:42:51.660
Then you use the Taylor
property that says 1 plus small

00:42:51.660 --> 00:42:55.380
is approximately equal
to 1 plus small over 2.

00:42:55.380 --> 00:42:59.320
And then you can
see that r equals

00:42:59.320 --> 00:43:07.750
z 1 plus x squared plus y
squared over z squared times 2,

00:43:07.750 --> 00:43:09.945
which is also known as z plus--

00:43:15.950 --> 00:43:16.540
OK.

00:43:16.540 --> 00:43:18.370
So that's the
paraxial approximation

00:43:18.370 --> 00:43:21.750
for the polar variable.

00:43:21.750 --> 00:43:26.020
And now I can, of course,
put it in my expression.

00:43:26.020 --> 00:43:30.750
So this means that e to the
ikr is approximately equal

00:43:30.750 --> 00:43:40.590
to e to the ikz, e to the ik, x
squared plus y squared over 2z.

00:43:40.590 --> 00:43:43.650
And sometimes we will
leave it like this.

00:43:43.650 --> 00:43:51.780
Or sometimes, we will remember
that k equals 2 pi upon lambda.

00:43:51.780 --> 00:43:58.830
And then this expression
now becomes e to the i 2 pi

00:43:58.830 --> 00:44:00.900
z upon lambda.

00:44:00.900 --> 00:44:02.730
e to the i, notice
what will happen.

00:44:02.730 --> 00:44:05.640
The 2s will cancel.

00:44:05.640 --> 00:44:07.290
A pi will remain.

00:44:07.290 --> 00:44:08.370
And you'll get--

00:44:12.600 --> 00:44:13.960
OK.

00:44:13.960 --> 00:44:16.520
So all of these are
interchangeable expressions

00:44:16.520 --> 00:44:19.590
that we can use for
spherical waves.

00:44:23.720 --> 00:44:26.580
Another interesting question--
I omitted something.

00:44:26.580 --> 00:44:30.262
I omitted 1 over ir.

00:44:30.262 --> 00:44:31.970
And actually, there's
also the amplitude.

00:44:31.970 --> 00:44:35.230
Let's put the amplitude
for completeness.

00:44:35.230 --> 00:44:37.560
What happens to the ir?

00:44:37.560 --> 00:44:42.240
Should they also do some
paraxial approximation over it?

00:44:42.240 --> 00:44:54.840
It turns out it is sufficient
to simply approximate it as z.

00:44:54.840 --> 00:45:00.000
For the part that appears
outside of the exponent,

00:45:00.000 --> 00:45:02.850
we can simply
approximate it as z.

00:45:02.850 --> 00:45:06.390
And the reason is because r,
it is actually slowly varying.

00:45:06.390 --> 00:45:08.720
You know, if you compare--

00:45:08.720 --> 00:45:11.920
what is r?

00:45:11.920 --> 00:45:13.150
Let's see if we can use the--

00:45:13.150 --> 00:45:17.733
yeah, so r is this, right?

00:45:17.733 --> 00:45:18.525
So if you compare--

00:45:35.450 --> 00:45:39.910
OK, so basically, you have
to pick z equals constant.

00:45:39.910 --> 00:45:42.240
So I have to pick
a plane that is

00:45:42.240 --> 00:45:44.760
tangential to the
sphere at this place.

00:45:44.760 --> 00:45:48.990
So I compare r1 to r2, right?

00:45:48.990 --> 00:45:53.710
So r1 goes all the way to the
plane. r2 simply stops here.

00:45:53.710 --> 00:45:56.530
So think about it this way.

00:45:56.530 --> 00:46:01.780
Let's say that the
error that they make--

00:46:01.780 --> 00:46:05.460
when I say z is
approximately equal to r,

00:46:05.460 --> 00:46:07.163
let's say that they
make a small error.

00:46:07.163 --> 00:46:08.830
Let's say that they
make an error of 1%.

00:46:12.360 --> 00:46:16.770
That means that they
misrepresent the amplitude

00:46:16.770 --> 00:46:19.850
of the wave by 1%.

00:46:19.850 --> 00:46:25.680
Now, let's look at the term
that is inside the exponential,

00:46:25.680 --> 00:46:30.080
e to the i pi xy, x squared
plus y squared over lambda z.

00:46:33.470 --> 00:46:41.320
If I miss by 1%, that is,
if I had e to the 1,000 pi

00:46:41.320 --> 00:46:50.270
and I miss by 1%, then it means
I went to e to the 990 pi,

00:46:50.270 --> 00:46:51.100
right?

00:46:51.100 --> 00:46:55.060
So this 1% error
actually caused me,

00:46:55.060 --> 00:46:59.410
how many, 10 full oscillations.

00:46:59.410 --> 00:47:02.680
That's why you have to
keep a better approximation

00:47:02.680 --> 00:47:09.840
inside the exponential than
I can afford to keep outside.

00:47:09.840 --> 00:47:15.360
So with the phase, I have to
be much more accurate in order

00:47:15.360 --> 00:47:18.120
to make sure that I don't make
a big error in the phase delay.

00:47:18.120 --> 00:47:21.510
And that's because the
cosine varies very rapidly.

00:47:21.510 --> 00:47:25.170
As you increase r, the
cosine is oscillating.

00:47:25.170 --> 00:47:28.710
But 1 over r is a slowly,
what we call a slowly varying

00:47:28.710 --> 00:47:30.270
function of r.

00:47:30.270 --> 00:47:33.540
And therefore, we can afford
to be sloppier with it,

00:47:33.540 --> 00:47:34.620
if you wish.

00:47:34.620 --> 00:47:37.770
So the paraxial approximation,
then, for the spherical wave

00:47:37.770 --> 00:47:45.850
is just like that with
z in the denominator

00:47:45.850 --> 00:47:50.523
but this additional quadratic
term in the exponent.

00:47:50.523 --> 00:47:52.440
And, of course, this
additional quadratic term

00:47:52.440 --> 00:47:55.770
is the one where all of
the action is happening.

00:47:55.770 --> 00:47:58.890
And this-- we will see
this later in the class.

00:47:58.890 --> 00:48:00.960
And that's the second
important lesson

00:48:00.960 --> 00:48:07.160
from today, which is that if
we see an expression which

00:48:07.160 --> 00:48:12.498
is quadratic in the
Cartesian coordinates,

00:48:12.498 --> 00:48:13.790
we'll call it a spherical wave.

00:48:16.550 --> 00:48:20.570
So we went through all
these adventures, I guess,

00:48:20.570 --> 00:48:25.210
to arrive at two
very basic waves.

00:48:25.210 --> 00:48:31.060
One is the kind of wave in whose
phasor you have linear terms

00:48:31.060 --> 00:48:33.520
in the cartesian coordinates.

00:48:33.520 --> 00:48:34.840
That we'll call the plane wave.

00:48:47.970 --> 00:48:51.895
OK, so if you see
something like this,

00:48:51.895 --> 00:48:54.020
it doesn't really matter
what these things are, kx,

00:48:54.020 --> 00:48:55.650
ky, and so on.

00:48:55.650 --> 00:49:01.110
But because these terms
are linear, it is plane.

00:49:01.110 --> 00:49:04.030
When you arrive at an
expression that looks like this,

00:49:04.030 --> 00:49:07.630
you might have
all kinds of junk.

00:49:07.630 --> 00:49:11.770
And somewhere you have something
of the form e to the i pi

00:49:11.770 --> 00:49:18.150
x squared plus y
squared over lambda z,

00:49:18.150 --> 00:49:29.100
this quadratic means that it is
spherical, or, more accurately,

00:49:29.100 --> 00:49:32.280
the paraxial approximation
to a spherical wave.

