00:57:11.850 --> 00:57:12.880
But you can do that.

00:57:12.880 --> 00:57:16.760
You can create waveguides.

00:57:16.760 --> 00:57:20.570
Actually, for visible light, you
will never actually use a metal

00:57:20.570 --> 00:57:21.540
here.

00:57:21.540 --> 00:57:23.570
You would use a
dielectric waveguide.

00:57:23.570 --> 00:57:26.430
But in microwaves, this
is done very commonly.

00:57:26.430 --> 00:57:33.020
In microwaves, people trap
the wave in a metal tube

00:57:33.020 --> 00:57:38.660
as if it were water, I suppose,
or some kind of a liquid.

00:57:38.660 --> 00:57:41.160
You just have a hollow
tube that is a metal.

00:57:41.160 --> 00:57:44.220
And then you launch the
microwave inside the tube.

00:57:44.220 --> 00:57:47.530
And to give you an idea,
the wavelength in microwaves

00:57:47.530 --> 00:57:49.040
is in the order of--

00:57:49.040 --> 00:57:56.150
well, as the name suggests,
it is the order of--

00:57:56.150 --> 00:57:58.370
the frequency's gigahertz.

00:57:58.370 --> 00:58:01.340
So the wavelength should
be between millimeters

00:58:01.340 --> 00:58:02.060
and centimeters.

00:58:02.060 --> 00:58:07.455
That is typically--
actually, less,

00:58:07.455 --> 00:58:09.080
no the wavelength is
a little bit less,

00:58:09.080 --> 00:58:10.870
maybe in the order
of millimeters,

00:58:10.870 --> 00:58:13.820
typical millimeter.

00:58:13.820 --> 00:58:16.098
So the size of these
tubes might also

00:58:16.098 --> 00:58:17.640
be on the order of
a few millimeters.

00:58:17.640 --> 00:58:21.200
So now you have a guide
that is approximately

00:58:21.200 --> 00:58:25.040
of size of a few wavelengths.

00:58:25.040 --> 00:58:29.140
So in that case, it turns this
equation, c equals lambda nu,

00:58:29.140 --> 00:58:30.790
does not hold anymore.

00:58:30.790 --> 00:58:32.740
It is true for a free space.

00:58:32.740 --> 00:58:35.080
But it is not true
in a waveguide.

00:58:35.080 --> 00:58:37.480
The reason it is not
true in a waveguide

00:58:37.480 --> 00:58:40.850
is because the wave must
satisfy boundary conditions.

00:58:40.850 --> 00:58:43.020
If you recall when we
gave the wave equation,

00:58:43.020 --> 00:58:45.490
we said we would need to
satisfy an initial condition

00:58:45.490 --> 00:58:47.070
and boundary conditions.

00:58:47.070 --> 00:58:49.595
In free space, there is
no boundary condition.

00:58:49.595 --> 00:58:51.220
Actually, there is
a boundary condition

00:58:51.220 --> 00:58:53.410
that the wave must
vanish with infinity.

00:58:53.410 --> 00:58:56.710
OK, fine, but that doesn't
have any implication

00:58:56.710 --> 00:58:59.860
in our calculations.

00:58:59.860 --> 00:59:02.140
But, for example, in
the case of a metal,

00:59:02.140 --> 00:59:06.790
you have to force the
wave to be 0 on the metal.

00:59:06.790 --> 00:59:09.940
Because, well, we'll see
later in electromagnetics

00:59:09.940 --> 00:59:10.990
why this is the case.

00:59:10.990 --> 00:59:13.300
But take my word for it.

00:59:16.920 --> 00:59:20.250
On the metal, the
