It will become evanescent.

01:00:47.510 --> 01:00:48.490
So it will not go in.

01:00:51.609 --> 01:00:52.442
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

01:00:56.900 --> 01:00:58.690
AUDIENCE: What is
shown in the diagram,

01:00:58.690 --> 01:01:00.800
isn't it a standing wave?

01:01:00.800 --> 01:01:03.530
Because it's not--
oscillation is--

01:01:06.940 --> 01:01:07.940
the way you have drawn--

01:01:07.940 --> 01:01:09.940
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: Yeah,
it is a standing wave

01:01:09.940 --> 01:01:11.480
in the vertical direction.

01:01:11.480 --> 01:01:13.105
AUDIENCE: Yeah, but
how does it propa--

01:01:13.105 --> 01:01:15.355
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: Well,
if the [INAUDIBLE] of it is

01:01:15.355 --> 01:01:16.490
bouncing back and forth--

01:01:16.490 --> 01:01:18.032
another way to think
of the waveguide

01:01:18.032 --> 01:01:20.970
is that the light is--

01:01:20.970 --> 01:01:23.100
you can think, actually,
in terms of rays.

01:01:23.100 --> 01:01:26.950
You can think of rays
bouncing back and forth.

01:01:26.950 --> 01:01:29.635
But you can also have
the conjugate ray.

01:01:29.635 --> 01:01:30.635
These are both possible.

01:01:34.230 --> 01:01:37.230
And the result is a standing
wave in this sentence.

01:01:37.230 --> 01:01:38.760
But you can still
have propagation

01:01:38.760 --> 01:01:39.780
on the horizontal axis.

01:01:39.780 --> 01:01:43.110
Because there is a component
that goes towards the right.

01:01:47.710 --> 01:01:54.850
OK, so when you get an
equation like this one which

01:01:54.850 --> 01:01:58.060
relates omega to k-- and, of
course, as you can imagine,

01:01:58.060 --> 01:02:00.820
now there's a great
variety of such equations

01:02:00.820 --> 01:02:01.780
that you could have.

01:02:01.780 --> 01:02:03.490
This is the equation
that happens to be

01:02:03.490 --> 01:02:05.470
true for the metal waveguide.

01:02:05.470 --> 01:02:07.840
If you replace it with
a different waveguide,

01:02:07.840 --> 01:02:10.050
for example, if you
have dielectrics

01:02:10.050 --> 01:02:14.530
of different indices here,
then this equation changes.

01:02:14.530 --> 01:02:16.840
The bottom line is that if
you have this equation, then

01:02:16.840 --> 01:02:18.630
you can plot one of the two.

01:02:18.630 --> 01:02:22.990
You have one term here that
is determined by geometry.

01:02:22.990 --> 01:02:25.540
a is the size of the guide.

01:02:25.540 --> 01:02:29.650
And then you have the wave
vector and the frequency.

01:02:29.650 --> 01:02:32.410
And, of course, you have
the free velocity of light.

01:02:32.410 --> 01:02:35.260
OK, omega is fundamental.

01:02:35.260 --> 01:02:37.100
As soon as you
specify the frequency

01:02:37.100 --> 01:02:39.100
of the electromagnetic
wave, nothing

01:02:39.100 --> 01:02:42.295
can change that anymore since
we're in the linear region.

01:02:42.295 --> 01:02:44.170
But the question is,
what is the wave vector?

01:02:44.170 --> 01:02:45.730
So the wave vector
is really what

01:02:45.730 --> 01:02:48.620
you are after in this equation.

01:02:48.620 --> 01:02:49.810
Omega is given.

01:02:49.810 --> 01:02:52.660
It is, say, 10 to the 15 Hertz.

01:02:52.660 --> 01:02:56.040
What is the k?

01:02:56.040 --> 01:02:58.540
Or in other words,
what is the wavelength?

01:02:58.540 --> 01:03:00.390
Now, for reasons which
will become apparent

01:03:00.390 --> 01:03:05.142
in a moment, the people who
invented these diagrams,

01:03:05.142 --> 01:03:07.350
they actually plot them kind
of the other way around.

01:03:07.350 --> 01:03:10.200
Instead of omega on
the horizontal axis,

01:03:10.200 --> 01:03:13.990
since omega is given, they put
omega on the vertical axis.

01:03:13.990 --> 01:03:16.330
And the horizontal axis is k.

01:03:16.330 --> 01:03:18.330
So the way you read this
diagram is-- of course,

01:03:18.330 --> 01:03:20.380
you solve this equation.

01:03:20.380 --> 01:03:22.590
And the way you read it
is that if I give you

01:03:22.590 --> 01:03:26.810
a certain omega, then you have
to draw a horizontal line.

01:03:26.810 --> 01:03:32.550
And wherever this horizontal
line meets the plot, this--

01:03:32.550 --> 01:03:35.312
you read the abscissa and--

01:03:35.312 --> 01:03:36.270
I never get this right.

01:03:36.270 --> 01:03:38.380
Is this the abscissa
or the other one?

01:03:38.380 --> 01:03:39.213
That's the abscissa?

01:03:39.213 --> 01:03:40.432
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:03:40.432 --> 01:03:42.140
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
That's the ordinate?

01:03:42.140 --> 01:03:43.788
OK.

01:03:43.788 --> 01:03:45.580
I must come up with a
mnemonic to remember.

01:03:45.580 --> 01:03:49.030
Anyway, so the value
of the horizontal axis

01:03:49.030 --> 01:03:52.660
gives you the wave vector,
and hence, the wavelength.

01:03:52.660 --> 01:03:55.908
Now, interestingly, if
you were in free space,

01:03:55.908 --> 01:03:57.450
this would look like
a straight line.

01:03:57.450 --> 01:04:00.420
Because, well, of
course in free space--

01:04:00.420 --> 01:04:02.400
I have written this
equation many times.

01:04:02.400 --> 01:04:04.500
I don't feel like
writing it again.

01:04:04.500 --> 01:04:07.930
In free space-- well,
let me do it once more.

01:04:07.930 --> 01:04:18.480
So in free space, I have
that c equals k over 2 pi.

01:04:18.480 --> 01:04:20.475
That's also known
as lambda times--

01:04:24.070 --> 01:04:25.920
what am I doing?

01:04:25.920 --> 01:04:26.940
The other way around--

01:04:26.940 --> 01:04:30.720
2 pi over k, that is
also known as lambda,

01:04:30.720 --> 01:04:33.460
times omega over 2 pi.

01:04:33.460 --> 01:04:38.700
So in free space, then,
you have omega equals ck.

01:04:38.700 --> 01:04:44.590
This is an equivalent way of
writing this equation here.

01:04:44.590 --> 01:04:46.950
These are basically
the same equation.

01:04:46.950 --> 01:04:50.520
So in free space, this
is a straight line.

01:04:54.770 --> 01:04:57.200
Now, if you have an
equation like this one,

01:04:57.200 --> 01:05:03.010
you can see that at
relatively high frequencies,

01:05:03.010 --> 01:05:04.030
they approach.

01:05:04.030 --> 01:05:07.100
So, indeed, all of the-- oh, by
the way, what are these curves?

01:05:07.100 --> 01:05:10.150
So this equation involves
an integral parameter.

01:05:10.150 --> 01:05:12.760
You can plug in--

01:05:12.760 --> 01:05:16.112
well, not quite 0, please
erase that from your notes.

01:05:16.112 --> 01:05:17.320
I should not have put 0 here.

01:05:17.320 --> 01:05:18.550
0 doesn't make sense.

01:05:18.550 --> 01:05:22.330
But you can have plus/minus
1, plus/minus 2, and so on.

01:05:22.330 --> 01:05:24.310
And these are known as modes.

01:05:24.310 --> 01:05:27.970
So the index defines
the mode that

01:05:27.970 --> 01:05:31.810
is launched into the waveguide.

01:05:31.810 --> 01:05:38.030
So each one of these modes,
at very high frequencies,

01:05:38.030 --> 01:05:41.690
it actually kind of approaches
the free space mode.

01:05:41.690 --> 01:05:44.030
But as you go to
lower frequencies,

01:05:44.030 --> 01:05:47.120
you see that it bends away
and then eventually hits

01:05:47.120 --> 01:05:49.900
the ordinate axis.

01:05:49.900 --> 01:05:51.620
And there's a gap here now.

01:05:51.620 --> 01:05:57.600
Because there's nothing
in this place over here.

01:05:57.600 --> 01:05:59.400
So what will happen
if you come up,

01:05:59.400 --> 01:06:03.200
if you use an omega that
falls in this range?

01:06:09.520 --> 01:06:10.660
AUDIENCE: Evanescent wave.

01:06:10.660 --> 01:06:12.660
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
Correct-- actually, someone

01:06:12.660 --> 01:06:13.830
asked it before in Boston.

01:06:13.830 --> 01:06:16.050
Someone asked me
before, what happens

01:06:16.050 --> 01:06:19.530
if you pick a to be
smaller than a wavelength?

01:06:19.530 --> 01:06:21.940
Well, this is what happens.

01:06:21.940 --> 01:06:25.250
In fact, I wouldn't espouse
it exactly like this.

01:06:25.250 --> 01:06:27.390
A more accurate way
to say it is what

01:06:27.390 --> 01:06:31.560
happens if you pick an
omega which is very small?

01:06:31.560 --> 01:06:36.060
So therefore, given the value of
a and given the value of omega,

01:06:36.060 --> 01:06:37.860
you cannot find the k anymore.

01:06:37.860 --> 01:06:40.130
The square root
becomes imaginary.

01:06:40.130 --> 01:06:42.950
Well, if that happens, the wave
does not enter the waveguide.

01:06:42.950 --> 01:06:44.730
It becomes
evanescent, as we say.

01:06:44.730 --> 01:06:46.800
So basically, it may
penetrate a little bit

01:06:46.800 --> 01:06:48.300
for a couple of wavelengths.

01:06:48.300 --> 01:06:51.930
And then it will
exponentially decay.

01:06:51.930 --> 01:06:55.500
Now, if you-- as you
go progressively-- so,

01:06:55.500 --> 01:06:57.600
if you launch at
very low frequency,

01:06:57.600 --> 01:06:59.800
the wave does not enter.

01:06:59.800 --> 01:07:03.360
As you start increasing
the frequency now,

01:07:03.360 --> 01:07:06.540
you will see that
the intersection only

01:07:06.540 --> 01:07:07.823
meets one mode.

01:07:07.823 --> 01:07:09.615
So basically, at the
range of frequencies--

01:07:09.615 --> 01:07:10.870
I don't know what it is here.

01:07:10.870 --> 01:07:13.230
This looks like 3 or something.

01:07:13.230 --> 01:07:16.290
So between-- so the
way you read this axis

01:07:16.290 --> 01:07:18.480
is you read the ordinate.

01:07:18.480 --> 01:07:21.570
And you multiply by
three times 10 to the 14.

01:07:21.570 --> 01:07:26.970
So, for example, 5
actually means 15 times 10

01:07:26.970 --> 01:07:28.620
to the 14 Hertz.

01:07:28.620 --> 01:07:32.130
OK, so then between
3, the value f3, which

01:07:32.130 --> 01:07:38.400
is 9 times 10 to the 14, and
the value, whatever it is, 7,

01:07:38.400 --> 01:07:40.830
you only launch one mode.

01:07:40.830 --> 01:07:44.180
As you go up in frequency,
if your intersection here

01:07:44.180 --> 01:07:46.800
meets more than one
line, then actually you

01:07:46.800 --> 01:07:51.050
can have multiple
modes in this guide.

01:07:51.050 --> 01:07:54.260
Anyway, so these modes,
these little wiggles

01:07:54.260 --> 01:07:56.940
that I drew over
here, the first mode

01:07:56.940 --> 01:08:00.480
is the field shape that
looks like this, only half

01:08:00.480 --> 01:08:02.360
of the period of the sinusoid.

01:08:02.360 --> 01:08:07.050
The next mode, you
allow one full period.

01:08:07.050 --> 01:08:09.330
The next mode, you
allow 1 1/2 period,

01:08:09.330 --> 01:08:10.770
then so on and so forth.

01:08:10.770 --> 01:08:12.750
So as you go higher
in frequency,

01:08:12.750 --> 01:08:14.370
it means that the wave--

01:08:14.370 --> 01:08:17.649
basically, what it means
is that the waveguide now--

01:08:17.649 --> 01:08:20.399
or, I should say the
wavelength of the wave

01:08:20.399 --> 01:08:24.540
becomes progressively smaller
than the size of the waveguide.

01:08:24.540 --> 01:08:29.649
So therefore, you can pack
more modes into the guide.

01:08:29.649 --> 01:08:31.123
So I only plotted three here.

01:08:31.123 --> 01:08:32.290
Of course, there's infinite.

01:08:32.290 --> 01:08:34.240
But anyway, as you
go up in frequency,

01:08:34.240 --> 01:08:37.270
you have the possibility to
excite more than one mode.

01:08:37.270 --> 01:08:38.743
Now, how do you
excite the modes?

01:08:38.743 --> 01:08:41.410
Now, that depends, of course, on
your initial conditions, right?

01:08:41.410 --> 01:08:44.080
If you create a
distribution in the entrance

01:08:44.080 --> 01:08:46.120
of the waveguide
that looks like this,

01:08:46.120 --> 01:08:47.620
then you will excite
the first mode.

01:08:47.620 --> 01:08:50.200
If you create a distribution
that looks like this,

01:08:50.200 --> 01:08:52.359
well, if the second
mode is allowable,

01:08:52.359 --> 01:08:55.029
that is if you are
above the green line,

01:08:55.029 --> 01:08:56.410
then you will excite it.

01:08:56.410 --> 01:08:57.939
If you are below
the green line, you

01:08:57.939 --> 01:08:59.350
will probably excite nothing.

01:08:59.350 --> 01:09:01.880
Because the first mode
cannot be excited this way.

01:09:05.727 --> 01:09:07.310
The reason I'm telling
you this is not

01:09:07.310 --> 01:09:10.069
because I want to do waveguide
theory, but because I

01:09:10.069 --> 01:09:12.920
but because I want to do
something that's called a beat.

01:09:12.920 --> 01:09:15.740
And a beat is an
extremely useful concept,

01:09:15.740 --> 01:09:19.770
both in the space domain
and in the time domain.

01:09:19.770 --> 01:09:22.189
So in the time domain,
the beat is actually--

01:09:22.189 --> 01:09:23.390
it is a very simple thing.

01:09:23.390 --> 01:09:25.460
It is defined as
the superposition

01:09:25.460 --> 01:09:30.390
of two sinusoids of slightly
different frequency.

01:09:30.390 --> 01:09:33.140
So we said this many times,
that if the wave is linear,

01:09:33.140 --> 01:09:35.569
therefore a
superposition is allowed.

01:09:35.569 --> 01:09:38.720
If I have two solutions
to the wave equation.

01:09:38.720 --> 01:09:39.560
I take the sum.

01:09:39.560 --> 01:09:41.819
It is still a solution.

01:09:41.819 --> 01:09:43.979
So now what you can
see here very easily--

01:09:43.979 --> 01:09:46.960
that's a diagram that I
stole from the textbook.

01:09:46.960 --> 01:09:50.779
Because the two waves have
slightly different frequency,

01:09:50.779 --> 01:09:51.890
they will misalign.

01:09:51.890 --> 01:09:55.400
So you can, for example,
start at the point

01:09:55.400 --> 01:09:58.172
where the waves are
exactly aligned.

01:09:58.172 --> 01:09:59.630
So they kind of
oscillate together.

01:09:59.630 --> 01:10:02.150
When one is positive,
the other is positive.

01:10:02.150 --> 01:10:03.860
But because the
period is different,

01:10:03.860 --> 01:10:06.350
or the frequency is
different, a little bit later,

01:10:06.350 --> 01:10:09.410
they will kind of separate.

01:10:09.410 --> 01:10:12.080
And now, over here, you can
see that this is the opposite.

01:10:12.080 --> 01:10:15.390
When one of them is positive,
the other is negative.

01:10:15.390 --> 01:10:17.750
And if you also happen
to judiciously pick

01:10:17.750 --> 01:10:19.790
them to have the
same amplitude, it

01:10:19.790 --> 01:10:24.240
means that here when, as we say,
they oscillate out of phase,

01:10:24.240 --> 01:10:30.210
it means that the wave amplitude
overall becomes very small.

01:10:30.210 --> 01:10:33.480
And so-- and of course,
in the other case,

01:10:33.480 --> 01:10:35.340
where they are in
phase, the amplitude

01:10:35.340 --> 01:10:38.010
becomes twice the
amplitude of one.

01:10:38.010 --> 01:10:41.190
So this is sort of a static
picture from the book.

01:10:41.190 --> 01:10:44.310
I also made a movie out of it.

01:10:44.310 --> 01:10:46.534
So here you see the
beat propagating.

01:10:50.800 --> 01:10:55.595
OK, so now, what is really
interesting about this--

01:10:55.595 --> 01:10:56.720
I'm going to play it again.

01:11:04.390 --> 01:11:06.370
If you look at it carefully--

01:11:06.370 --> 01:11:09.720
it takes a-- let me
play it once more.

01:11:09.720 --> 01:11:10.970
Actually, I think I can just--

01:11:19.790 --> 01:11:22.900
if you look at it
carefully, you will

01:11:22.900 --> 01:11:27.660
see that there is two
different velocities here.

01:11:30.072 --> 01:11:31.280
There's two things happening.

01:11:31.280 --> 01:11:37.120
One is you have this envelope
that is moving to the right.

01:11:37.120 --> 01:11:39.460
But also, inside
the envelope, you

01:11:39.460 --> 01:11:44.220
have small fringes, wiggles that
are also moving to the right.

01:11:44.220 --> 01:11:48.305
Now, I told you, of course,
but if you look at it once

01:11:48.305 --> 01:11:50.430
again more carefully, you
will see that the two are

01:11:50.430 --> 01:11:52.050
moving with different speeds.

01:11:56.610 --> 01:11:57.840
Can you see it?

01:12:00.750 --> 01:12:03.307
The wiggles are moving
faster than the envelope.

01:12:03.307 --> 01:12:05.390
And you can see that the
wiggles are moving faster

01:12:05.390 --> 01:12:07.830
than the envelop
if you look here

01:12:07.830 --> 01:12:10.095
near the vicinity of the null.

01:12:10.095 --> 01:12:11.970
You will see that there's
a little bit of a--

01:12:11.970 --> 01:12:14.820
once in a while, there's a
pulse, like a little pulse.

01:12:14.820 --> 01:12:18.390
That means that the
fringe are passing by.

01:12:18.390 --> 01:12:20.010
So the reason this
is happening--

01:12:20.010 --> 01:12:22.110
and now I will not
derive it on the paper.

01:12:22.110 --> 01:12:25.030
Because it will end
a little bit late.

01:12:25.030 --> 01:12:28.200
But the reason this
is happening is

01:12:28.200 --> 01:12:30.460
because if you take the
superposition of the two

01:12:30.460 --> 01:12:34.170
sinusoids, now we have to
be a little bit careful.

01:12:34.170 --> 01:12:37.180
Because they have
different frequencies.

01:12:37.180 --> 01:12:39.270
So if we use phasor--
we could use phasors.

01:12:39.270 --> 01:12:42.270
But we might get a
little bit confused.

01:12:42.270 --> 01:12:45.030
So for that reason, I just
wrote it in the real space

01:12:45.030 --> 01:12:46.363
simply with cosines.

01:12:46.363 --> 01:12:48.030
So you do the same
thing with it before.

01:12:48.030 --> 01:12:50.260
You take the sum
of the two cosines.

01:12:50.260 --> 01:12:52.170
You apply the
trigonometric identity

01:12:52.170 --> 01:12:53.910
to write it as a product.

01:12:53.910 --> 01:12:57.000
And then you find that the
product contains two terms.

01:12:57.000 --> 01:13:01.940
One of them-- actually,
by the way, the--

01:13:01.940 --> 01:13:02.630
oh, shoot.

01:13:02.630 --> 01:13:04.770
There's one more
error in the notes.

01:13:04.770 --> 01:13:07.800
There should be a cosine
between the two parentheses.

01:13:07.800 --> 01:13:10.200
There shouldn't be a cosine.

01:13:10.200 --> 01:13:12.286
I better write down
the correct expression.

01:13:37.630 --> 01:13:47.210
OK, where kc equals
k1 plus k2 over 2,

01:13:47.210 --> 01:13:57.340
and the same for omega c, and
km equals k1 minus k2 over 2,

01:13:57.340 --> 01:13:58.590
so one of them is the average.

01:13:58.590 --> 01:14:01.130
The other is the difference.

01:14:08.390 --> 01:14:12.220
So now each one of those,
each one of these cosines--

01:14:12.220 --> 01:14:13.680
OK, there's a
missing cosine here.

01:14:13.680 --> 01:14:15.437
But imagine that
there was a cosine.

01:14:15.437 --> 01:14:17.020
Each one of those
is a traveling wave.

01:14:20.010 --> 01:14:22.680
So basically, what you see
now is the product of the two

01:14:22.680 --> 01:14:23.460
traveling waves.

01:14:23.460 --> 01:14:26.430
And you can see very
clearly it's a product here.

01:14:26.430 --> 01:14:32.920
This is-- I have one sinusoid
of relatively low spatial period

01:14:32.920 --> 01:14:38.400
and another sinusoid of
relatively fast spatial period.

01:14:38.400 --> 01:14:39.562
And I multiply them.

01:14:39.562 --> 01:14:40.770
But they're both propagating.

01:14:40.770 --> 01:14:44.310
Because they're both of
the form kz minus omega t.

01:14:44.310 --> 01:14:47.220
But they're propagating
with different speeds.

01:14:47.220 --> 01:14:49.970
Because the speed of the--

01:14:49.970 --> 01:14:53.070
oh, and-- so, what
are the names?

01:14:53.070 --> 01:14:58.830
Well, the fast sinusoid
here is called the carrier.

01:14:58.830 --> 01:15:00.562
Those of you who are
electrical engineers

01:15:00.562 --> 01:15:01.770
are very familiar with those.

01:15:01.770 --> 01:15:03.990
The carrier wave is--

01:15:03.990 --> 01:15:09.450
in radiowaves, for example,
it is the frequency upon which

01:15:09.450 --> 01:15:11.910
we'll modulate the signal.

01:15:11.910 --> 01:15:20.630
And the slow sinusoid,
that's called the modulation.

01:15:20.630 --> 01:15:27.370
And-- I lost my
train of thought.

01:15:27.370 --> 01:15:31.270
All right, but each one of
those is a propagating wave.

01:15:31.270 --> 01:15:36.292
So therefore, their velocities
would be equal to the--

01:15:36.292 --> 01:15:38.250
it will depend on which
wave I'm talking about.

01:15:38.250 --> 01:15:40.960
So, for example, the
velocity of the carrier

01:15:40.960 --> 01:15:44.290
will equal omega of
the carrier divided

01:15:44.290 --> 01:15:46.270
by the k of the carrier.

01:15:46.270 --> 01:15:48.070
And the velocity
of the modulation

01:15:48.070 --> 01:15:50.110
will equal omega
of the modulation

01:15:50.110 --> 01:15:52.450
over k of the modulation.

01:15:52.450 --> 01:15:55.360
OK, and so this is not magic.

01:15:55.360 --> 01:15:57.430
We'll just apply the
theory that we learned.

01:15:57.430 --> 01:16:00.280
But now it is the two
waves that are propagating.

01:16:00.280 --> 01:16:03.670
And, of course, in general, the
two velocities are different.

01:16:03.670 --> 01:16:06.340
Because the two
rations over here,

01:16:06.340 --> 01:16:08.620
they have no reason
to be the same.

01:16:08.620 --> 01:16:10.240
In fact, it is
quite the opposite.

01:16:10.240 --> 01:16:12.350
Most of the time
they are different.

01:16:15.870 --> 01:16:21.230
So this velocity, I actually
used a slightly different

01:16:21.230 --> 01:16:22.220
notation.

01:16:22.220 --> 01:16:28.570
The velocity of the carrier
is called the phase velocity.

01:16:28.570 --> 01:16:30.280
And the velocity
of the modulation

01:16:30.280 --> 01:16:32.037
is called the group velocity.

01:16:50.940 --> 01:16:55.280
So the group velocity, it
equals, as you can see,

01:16:55.280 --> 01:16:59.260
the ratio of the
difference of omega

01:16:59.260 --> 01:17:02.990
to the ratio of the
difference of k.

01:17:02.990 --> 01:17:06.983
So if you imagine a beat--

01:17:06.983 --> 01:17:08.400
this is called a
beat, by the way.

01:17:08.400 --> 01:17:09.450
I think I said it before.

01:17:09.450 --> 01:17:12.900
So if you imagine a beat where
the two frequencies of the two

01:17:12.900 --> 01:17:16.463
numbers are very close, then
it will become the derivative.

01:17:21.770 --> 01:17:24.590
So the group
velocity is basically

01:17:24.590 --> 01:17:26.630
the derivative of the--

01:17:26.630 --> 01:17:29.960
whatever omega is
as a function of k,

01:17:29.960 --> 01:17:32.450
if you take the derivative
of that expression,

01:17:32.450 --> 01:17:33.980
you get the group velocity.

01:17:33.980 --> 01:17:37.070
The phase velocity
is the same velocity

01:17:37.070 --> 01:17:40.020
we've been talking about so
far while we're doing waves.

01:17:40.020 --> 01:17:43.040
So there's nothing new
about the phase velocity.

01:17:43.040 --> 01:17:47.480
It is still the ratio
of omega over k.

01:17:47.480 --> 01:17:50.060
But the group velocity
is the derivative.

01:17:50.060 --> 01:17:51.680
And the reason now--

01:17:51.680 --> 01:17:53.460
ah, now the reason is revealed.

01:17:53.460 --> 01:17:54.580
AUDIENCE: George?

01:17:54.580 --> 01:17:56.247
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
