01:17:56.247 --> 01:17:58.470
AUDIENCE: Yeah, why did
the derivative come about?

01:17:58.470 --> 01:18:00.350
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
Yeah, you're right.

01:18:00.350 --> 01:18:01.740
I kind of blasted through.

01:18:01.740 --> 01:18:04.300
So if you look at
the group velocity,

01:18:04.300 --> 01:18:07.760
it equals omega
of the modulation

01:18:07.760 --> 01:18:09.720
over k of the modulation.

01:18:09.720 --> 01:18:13.120
And this equals omega
1 minus omega 2 over 2

01:18:13.120 --> 01:18:16.250
over k1 minus k2 over 2.

01:18:16.250 --> 01:18:20.960
That is omega 1 minus
omega 2 over k1 minus k2.

01:18:20.960 --> 01:18:23.220
And if you take
omega one very close

01:18:23.220 --> 01:18:26.340
but not quite the
same and k1 very close

01:18:26.340 --> 01:18:30.167
but not quite the same, then v
sub g will become d omega dk.

01:18:33.510 --> 01:18:35.420
So that is the reason
people put omega

01:18:35.420 --> 01:18:37.440
on the vertical axis of it here.

01:18:37.440 --> 01:18:39.060
Because the group
velocity, then,

01:18:39.060 --> 01:18:44.900
is simply obtained as the slope
of the dispersion diagram.

01:18:44.900 --> 01:18:48.200
And that's fascinating,
